# Backend Spec

## Scope

Go API, domain boundaries, routes, persistence, cache, security, and store/auth
contracts.

## Load when

Changing backend handlers/services/repositories, routes, models, migrations,
auth, store, cache, WebSocket emission, uploads, SSR, or grengo proxy behavior.

## Owns

- Entry/router: `backend/main.go`
- Models: `backend/models/*.go`
- Domains: `backend/internal/{auth,user,forum,store,inbox,notification,config,page,datasource,customsection,events,upload,ws,ssr,grengo}`
- DB/Redis: `backend/database/db.go`
- Migrations: `backend/internal/migrations/*.sql`

## Architecture Contracts

- Go 1.24, chi/v5, raw SQL via `lib/pq`; no ORM.
- Domain shape is `handler => service => repository`.
- Handlers decode/validate HTTP and auth context only.
- Services own business rules, cache invalidation, event dispatch, and WS pushes.
- Repositories execute SQL, accept `context.Context` where the local interface
  does, and avoid business logic.
- Interfaces live per domain in `interface.go` for test substitution.
- Redis caches are best-effort, tenant-prefixed, read-through, and invalidated on writes.
- Normalized page-section values use the embedded Draft 2020-12 contracts through
  `s_registry.ValidateContractValue`; external schema references are forbidden,
  CSS colors receive explicit checks, and validation errors do not echo config.
- `backend/cmd/section-contract-gen` generates frontend and Go section config
  types/metadata; its check mode is part of backend/frontend drift verification.
- `s_registry.DecodeNormalizedSectionConfig` bounds input size/depth, rejects
  duplicate keys, validates the canonical schema, then returns a generated DTO.
- `pages.content` remains the custom-page read authority while
  `PAGE_NORMALIZED_SECTION_READS` is disabled or a page has not passed its
  cutover gate. Ready pages project reads only from normalized definition and
  response rows; projection/readiness failures fail closed instead of silently
  falling back after cutover.
- Shadow projection preserves page-scoped legacy identities and config encoding,
  records content-free parity/quarantine telemetry, and never copies interactive
  records or result summaries before the dedicated sensitive-data migration.
- `PAGE_TYPED_SECTION_MUTATIONS=1|true` enables typed writes only for pages whose
  latest shadow run is `matched`. The page service applies the centralized page
  editor policy, validates generated shell/config/item contracts, and the SQL
  repository checks expected revisions on locked rows before updating both the
  normalized source and legacy rollback projection in one transaction.
- `PAGE_NORMALIZED_INTERACTIVE_RESPONSES=1|true` enables normalized response
  authority only after matched page definition and response-migration runs.
  Reads inject normalized rows into a temporary authorization-filtered page
  projection; storage or readiness failures remove runtime data and deny writes.
- `PAGE_NORMALIZED_SECTION_READS=1|true` requires matched definition and response
  migration state, no quarantine, the configured consecutive zero-diff window,
  and a successful rollback drill for each page. Defaults are three observations
  and 24 hours; disabling the flag immediately restores compatibility reads.

## Middleware Contracts

| Layer | Contract |
| --- | --- |
| CORS | Explicit `DOMAINS` allowlist; no wildcard production origins |
| JWT | `Authorization: Bearer <token>` injects claims |
| Optional JWT | Enriches anonymous reads without blocking |
| MFA/IP hopping | Auth-sensitive middleware runs under `/api` |
| Permission | RBAC by permission string; admin role implies all permissions |
| Rate limit | General/auth/defcon limiters are per IP |
| Armed guard | Blocks API traffic while tenant is armed except allowlisted paths |
| API cache | JSON responses are `no-store` via `utils.WriteJSON/WriteError` |

## Auth Contracts

- JWT access tokens use HS256 and `SESSION_TIMEOUT_MIN` (default 30 minutes).
- Refresh tokens are stateful and stored in `user_sessions`.
- Passwords use bcrypt cost 12 and 8-72 character validation.
- Credentials, TOTP secrets, and backup codes are auth-owned tables, not `users`.
- Role/permission changes push `user:update permissions_changed` with a fresh token.
- MFA-required state can be pushed as `mfa:required` / user update challenge events.

